{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"608ea67e-c6c3-4160-ae4b-732259fd9df6","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command: \"dotnet\"`** with `args: [\"run\", \"--project\", ...]` builds and runs your server.\n- For a **published** build, use `\"command\": \"dotnet\"` with `\"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]` instead.\n- Make sure your server uses **stdio transport** (not HTTP) — e.g., `.WithStdioServerTransport()` in your `Program.cs`.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat in **Agent mode** (`@workspace`) and it will auto-discover the tools exposed by your server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f235b1ff-8db6-4edc-ab6c-e133a6f7f6f5","outputTokens":325,"requestId":"3C06:2310B5:202B8B9:2412E81:69E81D0B"},"id":"7ab3b6b3-16a1-4fc4-af5c-139b7a805e22","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:57:55.954Z","parentId":"c4227f14-f2e4-4b2f-8b56-abeb44ff4395"}
